After a disconsolate five minutes of solitude , Bertram got his hat and coat and went out for his walk but he told himself he did not expect to enjoy it . 
Bertram Henshaw knew that the old rebellious jealousy of the summer had him fast in its grip . 
He was heartily ashamed of himself , but he could not help it . 
He wanted Billy , and he wanted her then . 
He wanted to talk to her . 
The sweetest melody in the world , if dinned into one's ears day and night , became something to be fled from . 
And Billy ought to talk of something else , too ! Bertram , Jr . 
But Billy seemed to have forgotten this . 
If it had not been so serious , it would have been really funny the way all roads led straight to one goal . 
He never , however , found one . 
But it was not funny it was serious . 
He must he patient , and wait . 
He was sure she did . 
By and by this obsession of motherhood , which had her so fast in its grasp , would relax . 
She would remember that her husband had rights as well as her child . 
Once again she would give him the companionship , love , and sympathetic interest so dear to him . 
Meanwhile there was his work . 
He must bury himself in that . 
And fortunate , indeed , he was , he told himself , that he had something so absorbing . 
In the old days he had liked this Bob Seaver well . 
Seaver was an artist like himself , and was good company always . 
But Seaver and his crowd were a little too Bohemian for William's taste and after Billy came , she , too , had objected to what she called that horrid Seaver man . 
To night , however , Seaver's genial smile and hearty friendliness were like a sudden burst of sunshine on a rainy day and Bertram detested rainy days . 
He was feeling now , too , as if he had just had a whole week of them . 
Yes , I am something of a stranger here , '' nodded Seaver . 
